  "final_answer": "Using low satisfaction as a proxy for high stress, there are 8 students who appear to have high stress despite relatively low daily usage/study hours (<= 1.8 hours/day).\n\nWho they are:\n- IDs: 1, 3, 38, 41, 57, 65, 79, 86\n- Average age: 19\n- Average daily usage: 1.06 hours/day\n\nPatterns that may help explain it:\n- Mixed academic stage:\n  - 4 are in School\n  - 4 are in College\n  - This suggests the issue is not limited to one education level.\n- Slightly more female students:\n  - 5 female\n  - 3 male\n- Evenly spread across cities:\n  - Lahore: 2\n  - Multan: 2\n  - Faisalabad: 2\n  - Karachi: 2\n  - So location does not appear to be the main driver here.\n- Common use cases:\n  - Writing: 3\n  - Research: 2\n  - Coding: 2\n  - Learning: 1\n  - Writing-related tasks show up most often, which may reflect pressure from assignments or deadlines.\n- Grade outcomes are often not improving:\n  - No Change: 4\n  - Improved: 3\n  - Slight Decline: 1\n  - Low satisfaction paired with little academic gain may help explain stress even when usage hours are low.\n- Tool use is mixed:\n  - ChatGPT: 3\n  - Gemini: 3\n  - Copilot: 1\n  - Notion AI: 1\n  - This suggests stress is probably not tied to one specific tool.\n\nMost likely explanation:\n- These students may not be stressed because of the number of hours they spend, but because their time is not translating into better outcomes.\n- Pressure around writing, research, or academic performance may be contributing more than raw study time.\n- Since many report no change in grades, frustration or unmet expectations could be a key factor.\n\nImportant note:\n- The dataset does not include a direct stress variable, so this finding is based on low satisfaction as a stress proxy, not a direct stress measurement.",
